Missing data & outliers

If there are less than 5% of missing data values, the best solution is to remove the cases from the dataset. However if it is a high number of cases of missing data, the best idea is to impute the values with the mean just to check the correlation with the other attributes, and then due to having such a high number of missing data cases, the whole attribute is not precise so it would finally be dumped from the dataset.

def plotAttribute(featureName):
    plt.rc('font', size=15)
    oneSTD = data[featureName].std()
    twoSTD = oneSTD * 2
    threeSTD = oneSTD * 3
    meanValue = data[featureName].mean()
    
    print("Attribute:", featureName.upper())
    print("Summary:")
    
    instances = data.shape[0]
    outsideTwo = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - twoSTD)).sum() + (data[featureName] > (meanValue + twoSTD)).sum())
    outsideThree = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - threeSTD)).sum() + (data[featureName] > (meanValue + threeSTD)).sum())
    
    print("N outside of two STD:\t", outsideTwo, "\t(", round((outsideTwo/instances) *100, 2),"%)")
    print("N outside of three STD:\t", outsideThree, "\t(", round((outsideThree/instances) * 100, 2),"%)")
    
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - oneSTD), label='One STD', c="g")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + oneSTD), c="g")
    
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - twoSTD), label='Two STD', c="y")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + twoSTD), c="y")

    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - threeSTD), label='Three STD', c="r")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + threeSTD), c="r")
    
    data[featureName].hist(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
for attribute in myAtt:
    plotAttribute(attribute)

Question 2

Now that we have visualized the specific 4 attributes and made the necessary calculations, we can now identify the missing data and outliers.

  • solidity: There is no missing data for this attribute as there are no negative values. However, we can see that there are 145 instances that fall outside of 3 STDs. Given the size of the dataset, these instances only account for 1.78%. Seen as this is lower than 5% of the population, we will remove these instances.
  • aspectRatio: There is no missing data for this attribute as there are no negative values. However, there is a small number of instances (7) that fall outside of 3 STDs. Seen as these instances only take up 0.09% of the population, they will be removed.
  • minorAxisLength: There is no missing data for this attribute as there are no negative values. However, we can find that there are 310 instances outside of 3 STDs which make up for 3.8% of the population. Therfore, as it is less than 5% of the population, these instances will be removed.
  • area: There is no missing data for this attribute as there are no negative values. However, there are 295 instances that are outside of 3 STDs which represents less than 5% of the population. Therefore, these instances will be removed.

Question 3

As we mentioned in the previous question, we are going to be removing all the instances where the value of one or more of the 4 attributes fall outside of 3 STDs. We can do this in a single marking and cleaning of data.

Marking the data

In [ ]:
for att in myAtt:
    meanValue = data[att].mean()
    threeSTD = 3*(data[att].std())
    data[att] = data[att].mask(data[att] < meanValue - threeSTD, np.NaN)
    data[att] = data[att].mask(data[att] > meanValue + threeSTD, np.NaN)

When it comes to the 4 specific attributes we can see that there is a strong correlation between area and minorAxisLength which is to be expected as one can be used to calculate the other. However, it is interesting to note that in the scatter plots we can identify some clusters in the plots of aspectRatio with minorAxisLength and aspectRatio and area. Despite there being a high correlation between minorAxisLength and area, I would not include both of them in the set of multicollinear attributes. Therefore, I would choose solidity, aspectRatio and area.


There are many attributes with a strong correlation between them but most of them are because one could be used to calculate the other, like for example, perimeter and area. Therefore, the set I would choose would be formed by compactness, shapeFactor3 and shapeFactor2.
